\end_layout

\end_inset

 Which is the connectivity structure within the network.
 The latter is usually defined in terms of populations which represent neurons
 of the same type in a specific cortical area.
 The type of a neuron can be characterized by e.g.
 its morphology, its electrophysiological properties, or functional properties
 (e.g.
 receptivity to a specific stimulus feature).
 Neurons within a population are considered to be statistical identical,
 i.e.
 they form on average the same number of connections with neurons of other
 types.
 The strength of each individual connection is drawn randomly from a distributio
n which may differ depending on the type of the pre- and postsynaptic neuron.
 Parameters which define the neuron model are often assumed to be identical
 for all neurons in the same population have the same parameters.
 In this setting, one is usually not interested in the dynamical features
 of individual neurons, but instead on the dynamical features of the populations
 as a whole like e.g.
 the average population firing rate, interspike interval statistics (ISI),
 or the statistics of pairwise or higher order correlations between neuron
 activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In theoretical neuroscience, neuronal dynamics are studied analytically.
 From a mathematical viewpoint, describing how the network state evolves
 in time boils down to solving a large system coupled differential equation.
 Due to the non linearity of the neuron dynamics and the complex interactions
 between neurons, there is no hope to derive an exact solution.
 Hence, approximation schemes are needed.
 A commonly used method in theoretical neuroscience is mean-field theory
 which makes use of the assumed homogeneity described before [].
 Its main idea is to decouple the system of differential equations which
 describes network dynamics by approximating the input each neuron receives
 by the average input all neurons receive within the same population.
 Next, the output for each neuron must be determined given we know the input.
 Because neurons in the same populations are assumed to be statistical identical
, they can all be described by the same input output relationship often
 referred to as the mean-field equation.
 Hence, mean-field theory reduces the dimensionalty of the initial problem
 to a system of equations with size equal to number of populations.
 Note the output of each neuron is fed back into the network via the recurrent
 connections, and therefore contributes to input of other neurons.
 Hence, to solve the mean-field equations in a consistent manner, one need
 to identify those values for the input which yield an average output which
 is consistent with the initial input.
 
\end_layout

