\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gaussian white noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, we assume that the sum in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: current-based synapse"

\end_inset

 contains only a single type of synapses.
 In a network context, for an arbitrary neuron 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: synaptic current"

\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{\text{s},i}(t)=\tau_{\text{m}}\sum_{j=1}^{K_{i}}I_{ij}(t),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For delta-synapses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: delta synapse"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{ij}(t)$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{ij}(t)=J_{ij}\sum_{n=1}\delta(t-t_{n}^{(ij)})\label{eq: delta synapse-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using the mean-field ansatz introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-population-density"

\end_inset

, we replace all quantities in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: delta synapse-1"

\end_inset

 by their population averaged counterparts such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{\text{s}}(t)=\tau_{\text{m}}J\sum_{n}\delta(t-t_{n}^{(i)}),\label{eq: synaptic current-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\bigl\langle K_{i}\bigr\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\bigl\langle J_{ij}\bigr\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The spike times are Poisson distributed with rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Kr(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The number of indegrees a cortical neuron receives are typically in the
 order of 
\begin_inset Formula $K\sim\mathcal{O}(10^{3}$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $10^{4})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Braitenberg2013"

\end_inset

 and firing rates are in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)\sim\mathcal{O}(1$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2})$
\end_inset

Hz 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Source TODO
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Hence, neurons receive a large number of inputs in a time interval of the
 size of the membrane time constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\text{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 If the individually inputs cause only a small change in the membrane potential,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is small compared to the distance from the reset value 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{r}}$
\end_inset

 to threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\text{s}}(t)$
\end_inset

 can be approximated by a Gaussian white noise which is illustrated in Fig.
 
